                                          <div class="footnote-item" id="footnote8_js2qa7i"><a class="footnote-label" href="#footnoteref8_js2qa7i">8.</a><div class="footnote-text">“Habermas’ Public Sphere”, Part II, Chapter 17, in <em>Media Studies 101: A Creative Commons Textbook</em>, (Victoria, BC: BC Open Textbook Collection, 2018), 42–44, <a href="http://solr.bccampus.ca:8001/bcc/file/e700f1ca-aadb-481c-a30f-180cbf2eb80c/1/Media-Studies-101-1540433146._print.pdf">http://solr.bccampus.ca:8001/bcc/file/e700f1ca-aadb-481c-a30f-180cbf2eb80c/1/Media-Studies-101-1540433146._print.pdf</a>.</div></div>
                                          <div class="footnote-item" id="footnote9_yg9w43b"><a class="footnote-label" href="#footnoteref9_yg9w43b">9.</a><div class="footnote-text">W Lance Bennett and Steven Livingston, “The Disinformation Order: Disruptive Communication and the Decline of Democratic Institutions”, <em>European Journal of Communication</em>, Volume <em>33</em>, Issue 2, April 2018, 122–139,&nbsp;<a href="https://doi.org/10.1177/0267323118760317">https://doi.org/10.1177/0267323118760317</a>.</div></div>
